{"title_page": "Old Holbrook", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                 England\n|static_image=             Unnamed field inbetween Upper Rapeland Wood and Lower Rapeland Plantation, Old Holbrook. March 2020.jpg\n|static_image_width=             340px\n|static_image_caption=     Farmland facing Upper Rapeland Wood\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.091970|-0.318035|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name =           Old Holbrook\n|population =              \n|shire_district=           [[Horsham (district)|Horsham]]\n|shire_county=             [[West Sussex]]  \n|region=                   South East England\n|post_town=                \n|postcode_district =       \n|postcode_area=            \n|dial_code=                \n|os_grid_reference=        TQ184339\n}}\n\n'''Old Holbrook''' (formerly known as '''Northlands''') is a [[Hamlet (place)|hamlet]] in the [[Horsham (district)|Horsham]] district of [[West Sussex]], England. This rural hamlet is located north of the [[Horsham]] residential area of [[Horsham#Holbrook|Holbrook]] beyond the [[A264]]. It is bordered by [[Graylands]] to the west, Wimlands to the east, and Green Lane on its northern perimeter.\n\n==History==\nThe etymology of '''Old Holbrook''' has changed throughout history.\n\nThe name ''Holbrook'' itself originates from the feeder stream of the River Arun. Prior to the construction of the [[A264]] dual carriageway, the area was simply known as ''Northlands'', named after a farm located on Rapeland Hill. After the completion of the [[A264]] in 1989, the main lane was renamed ''Old Holbrook'' to distinguish it from the newer [[Horsham]] residential area of ''Holbrook''.\n\nOld Holbrook has a largely agricultural history, with scattered farmhouses dating from the 16th century post-medieval period. Established in 1537, Rapeland Farm remains one of the oldest properties located in the hamlet. ''Rapeland'' gives its name to 'a place where rape grows', referring to [[rapeseed]] plants.<ref name=\"wordpress\">{{cite web|url=https://northhorsham.files.wordpress.com/2018/09/ase-heritage-statement.pdf|date=May 2016|title=Land North of Horsham, West Sussex: Historic Environment Desk-Based Assessment (Heritage Statement)|publisher=Archaeology South-East|author=Richard James|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the south of the hamlet, there exists a historical 17th century moated house, formerly occupied by Horsham member of parliament [[Robert Henry Hurst (junior)|Robert Henry Hurst]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/sussex/vol6/pt2/pp131-156#fnn313|title=Horsham: General history of the town &#124; British History Online|website=www.british-history.ac.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, a [[crop circle]] appeared in a field of young wheat adjacent to Upper Rapeland Wood, in the north of the hamlet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.getsurrey.co.uk/lifestyle/fun-stuff/crop-circles-footage-reveals-mystery-9854340|title=Crop circles spotted in Surrey - but how did they get there?|first=Eleanor|last=Davis|date=14 August 2015|website=getsurrey}}</ref>\n\n[[File:A map of Old Holbrook, circa 1937.png|thumb|left|A map of Old Holbrook, circa 1937.]]\n\n== Topography ==\nOld Holbrook is a hamlet of small irregular fields bounded by hedgerows and intermixed with grazing and woodland. The hamlet sits on Rapeland Hill, reaching an elevation of 194 feet above sea level.\n\nSpecific features include;\n*'''[[Upper Rapeland Wood]]''';  a large block of mixed mature woodland\n*'''[[Holming Wood]]'''; mature mixed woodland.\n*'''Lower Rapeland Plantation'''; mature mixed woodland with ancient oaks.\n*'''Furzefield Copse''';  mixed woodland with ancient oaks.\n*'''Hurst Wood'''; mixed woodland with ancient oaks\n*'''Barn Coppice'''; the sole ancient woodland defined by a woodbank and former quarry pit in the centre, now landscaped as a pond with the surroundings cleared of trees. <ref>https://northhorsham.files.wordpress.com/2018/09/ase-heritage-statement.pdf p.23</ref>\n*'''Northlands Gill'''; a narrow stream stretching the entire width of both [[Graylands]] and Old Holbrook.\n\n== Industry ==\nOld Holbrook is a rural area, and therefore is largely agrarian. This is reflected in the more forested north and central parts of the hamlet, where crops are grown and animal husbandry is practised.\n\nThe southern half of the hamlet is less forested with a lower elevation, making it more suitable for more contemporary commercial businesses. This area hosts a swimming school, a nursery school and an animal rescue shelter.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n{{Horsham|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hamlets in West Sussex]]\n[[Category:Horsham District]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                 England\n|static_image=             Unnamed field inbetween Upper Rapeland Wood and Lower Rapeland Plantation, Old Holbrook. March 2020.jpg\n|static_image_width=             340px\n|static_image_caption=     Farmland facing Upper Rapeland Wood\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.091970|-0.318035|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name =           Old Holbrook\n|population =              \n|shire_district=           [[Horsham (district)|Horsham]]\n|shire_county=             [[West Sussex]]  \n|region=                   South East England\n|post_town=                \n|postcode_district =       \n|postcode_area=            \n|dial_code=                \n|os_grid_reference=        TQ184339\n}}\n\n'''Old Holbrook''' (formerly known as '''Northlands''') is a [[Hamlet (place)|hamlet]] in the [[Horsham (district)|Horsham]] district of [[West Sussex]], England. This rural hamlet is located north of the [[Horsham]] residential area of [[Horsham#Holbrook|Holbrook]] beyond the [[A264]]. It is bordered by [[Graylands]] to the west, Wimlands to the east, and Green Lane on its northern perimeter.\n\n==History==\nThe etymology of '''Old Holbrook''' has changed throughout history.\n\nThe name ''Holbrook'' itself originates from the feeder stream of the River Arun. Prior to the construction of the [[A264]] dual carriageway, the area was simply known as ''Northlands'', named after a farm located on Rapeland Hill. After the completion of the [[A264]] in 1989, the main lane was renamed ''Old Holbrook'' to distinguish it from the newer [[Horsham]] residential area of ''Holbrook''.\n\nOld Holbrook has a largely agricultural history, with scattered farmhouses dating from the 16th century post-medieval period. Established in 1537, Rapeland Farm remains one of the oldest properties located in the hamlet. ''Rapeland'' gives its name to 'a place where rape grows', referring to [[rapeseed]] plants.<ref name=\"wordpress\">{{cite web|url=https://northhorsham.files.wordpress.com/2018/09/ase-heritage-statement.pdf|date=May 2016|title=Land North of Horsham, West Sussex: Historic Environment Desk-Based Assessment (Heritage Statement)|publisher=Archaeology South-East|author=Richard James|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the south of the hamlet, there exists a historical 17th century moated house, formerly occupied by Horsham member of parliament [[Robert Henry Hurst (junior)|Robert Henry Hurst]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/sussex/vol6/pt2/pp131-156#fnn313|title=Horsham: General history of the town &#124; British History Online|website=www.british-history.ac.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, a [[crop circle]] appeared in a field of young wheat adjacent to Upper Rapeland Wood, in the north of the hamlet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.getsurrey.co.uk/lifestyle/fun-stuff/crop-circles-footage-reveals-mystery-9854340|title=Crop circles spotted in Surrey - but how did they get there?|first=Eleanor|last=Davis|date=14 August 2015|website=getsurrey}}</ref>\n\n[[File:A map of Old Holbrook, circa 1937.png|thumb|left|A map of Old Holbrook, circa 1937.]]\n\n== Topography ==\nOld Holbrook is a hamlet of small irregular fields bounded by hedgerows and intermixed with grazing and woodland. The hamlet sits on Rapeland Hill, reaching an elevation of 194 feet above sea level.\n\nSpecific features include;\n*'''[[Upper Rapeland Wood]]''';  a large block of mixed mature woodland\n*'''[[Holming Wood]]'''; mature mixed woodland.\n*'''Lower Rapeland Plantation'''; mature mixed woodland with ancient oaks.\n*'''Furzefield Copse''';  mixed woodland with ancient oaks.\n*'''Hurst Wood'''; mixed woodland with ancient oaks\n*'''Unnamed ancient woodland'''; the sole ancient woodland defined by a woodbank and former quarry pit in the centre, now landscaped as a pond with the surroundings cleared of trees.\n*'''Northlands Gill'''; a narrow stream stretching the entire width of both [[Graylands]] and Old Holbrook.\n\n== Industry ==\nOld Holbrook is a rural area, and therefore is largely agrarian. This is reflected in the more forested north and central parts of the hamlet, where crops are grown and animal husbandry is practised.\n\nThe southern half of the hamlet is less forested with a lower elevation, making it more suitable for more contemporary commercial businesses. This area hosts a swimming school, a nursery school and an animal rescue shelter.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n{{Horsham|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hamlets in West Sussex]]\n[[Category:Horsham District]]\n", "name_user": "Poleg\u00e5arden", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTopography:Unnamed ancient woodland > Barn Coppice >", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Holbrook"}
{"title_page": "Margaret Gray Evans", "text_new": "[[File:Margaret Gray Evans.png|thumb|Margaret Gray Evans, wife of [[John Evans (Colorado governor)|John Evans]], governor of [[Colorado Territory]], Northwestern University Archives]]\n'''Margaret Gray Evans''' (August 21, 1830\u2013September 7, 1906) was the wife of Territorial Governor [[John Evans (Colorado governor)|John Evans]] and was a philanthropist. She arrived in Denver when it was a rough city, having grown up in a privileged home in Maine. Evans was First Lady of Colorado for her husband and her son-in-law, [[Samuel Hitt Elbert]], who was a widower when he became governor. She was known for creating Denver society for the manner in which she entertained in what was the executive manor in Colorado. She assisted her husband on his educational and civil projects, and created her own. She founded the Denver Orphan's Home and was involved in the establishment of literary and charitable organizations. She was also active on boards of the [[University of Denver]]. She was the mother of [[William Gray Evans]] and [[Anne Evans (arts patron)|Anne Evans]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nMargaret Patten Gray was born on August 21, 1830<ref name=\"DPL\">{{Cite web |url=http://eadsrv.denverlibrary.org/sdx/pl/doc-tdm.xsp?id=WH1724_d0e34&fmt=text&base=fa |title=Governor John Evans Papers, WH1724, Western History Collection |website=The Denver Public Library  |access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref><ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|19}} in [[Bowdoinham, Maine]]. She was one of nine children born to Susan Felton Gray and Samuel Gray, a lawyer and shipbuilder.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|19}}\n\n[[Image:Mayflower in Plymouth Harbor, by William Halsall.jpg|thumb|''Mayflower in Plymouth Harbor'' by [[William Halsall]] (1882)]]\nShe is one of the [[Daughters of the American Revolution]] through her great-grandfather Pardon Gray and a descendant of two men on the ''[[Mayflower]]'', [[Francis Cooke]] and [[Richard Warren]].<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|19}}\n\nHer sister Cornelia married [[Orrington Lunt]], a wealthy grain broker who also helped found [[Northwestern University]] with John Evans. [[Paul Cornell (lawyer)|Paul Cornell]], an attorney, married another sister. Cornell was a real estate developer who founded\nthe town of [[Hyde Park, Illinois]].<ref name=\"Northwestern Study\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.northwestern.edu/provost/committees/equity-and-inclusion/study-committee-report.pdf|title=Report of the John Evans Study Committee: Chapter Two - The Life and Career of John Evans |date=May 2014 |website=Northwestern University |access-date=February 7, 2020|pages=15\u201317, 99}}</ref>\n\n==Marriage and children==\nMargaret Gray married John Evans August 18, 1853 in Bowdoinham, Maine.<ref name=\"DPL\" /><ref name=\"Northwestern Study\" /> It was the second marriage for John Evans, whose wife, Hannah Canby Evans, died of [[tuberculosis]] in 1850. She had a step-daughter, [[Josephine Evans Elbert|Josephine Evans]], the only surviving child from his first marriage.<ref name=\"Northwestern Study\" /> The family moved to Chicago in 1855.<ref name=\"Northwestern Study\" /> \n\nMargaret and John's children are:\n* [[William Gray Evans]], born on December 16, 1855 in Chicago<ref name=\"DPL\" /><ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|20}}\n* Margaret Evans, born October 3, 1857 in Chicago and died at age 5 of [[scarlet fever]] in 1862<ref name=\"DPL\" /><ref name=\"Northwestern Study\" /><ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|20\u201321}} \n* Evan Elbert Evans, born June 26, 1863 in Evanston, Illinois<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|23}}{{efn|Evan is said to be born in Denver,<ref name=\"DPL\" /> but an article about Margaret Gray Evans states that she returned to Evanston for the birth of their child.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|23}}}} Married to Kathryn Farrell of West Virginia, his stepdaughter was Madelyn Evans. He was a businessman in California, and then ran the Evans Investment Company. He died in 1921.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://research.frick.org/directory/viewItem/4777 |title=Archives Directory for the History of Collecting in America |website=research.frick.org |access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Anne Evans (arts patron)|Anne Evans]] born January 23, 1871<ref name=\"DPL\" /><ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|27}}\n\nTheir daughter, Margaret, died a few months after John Evans moved to Denver while the rest of the family remained in [[Evanston, Illinois]].<ref name=\"Northwestern Study\" /> Margaret and her son William moved to Colorado in November 1862 when her husband had sufficiently settled his affairs. They initially lived at Tremont House while their house was built. Josephine went away to school at the [[Wilbraham Wesleyan Academy]] in Wilbraham, Massachusetts. After she completed her schooling, she moved to Denver in late January 1864.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|21\u201322}} \n\nMargaret traveled to Washington, D.C. with her stepdaughter Josephine and niece Cornelia Gray Lunt to attend [[Abraham Lincoln]]'s second inauguration. She also traveled to Evanston when Josephine married [[Samuel Hitt Elbert]] in 1865 at the Evanston home.<ref name=\"Northwestern Study\" /><ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|23}} Josephine had a child who died in 1868. She died of tuberculosis in 1868.<ref name=\"Northwestern Study\" />\n\nMargaret lived in London, England in the mid-1870s, during which John Evans had experienced losses due to mining and railroad investments.<ref name=\"Northwestern Study\" />\n\n==First Lady==\n[[File:John Evans House, Denver, about 1870s.png|thumb|John Evans House, Denver, about 1870s]]\nShe became the First Lady of the Colorado Territory when her husband became the Territorial governor of [[Colorado Territory]] in 1862. Since [[William Gilpin (governor)|William Gilpin]], the first governor, was a bachelor, she was the first First Lady. Their home at 14th and Arapahoe Streets in Denver was the executive manor of the territory. While houses at the time were rough, low-roofed cabins, they lived in a one and a half story brick house. She built a significant library in the house. They lived there from 1863 to 1900.<ref name=\"First Ladies\">{{Cite magazine |last=Cannon |first=Helen |date=January 1962 |title=First Ladies of Colorado-Margaret Gray Evans  |url=https://www.historycolorado.org/sites/default/files/media/document/2018/ColoradoMagazine_v39n1_January1962.pdf |magazine=Colorado Magazine |pages=19-28 |access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|19, 21\u2013 23}}\n\nDuring her husband's administration, there was a flood and fire in Denver, famine, and fear of attacks by Native Americans.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|23}} Despite the difficulties, she organized Denver society with her friends who were also well-educated and dignified. People of the period stated that Denver society began with Margaret Gray Evans when she and her husband began entertaining members of the legislature in their home. It was the beginning of the many times that Margaret and her husband entertained. She was known for creating elegant evenings of music, lively conversation, and joy. Her skills were learned from \"the hospitable\nand cultured but precise New England home of her girlhood.\"<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|23\u201325}}\n\nIn the 1870s, she supervised the expansion of their home into a three-story house, which served again as an executive manor when her son-in-law became the governor from 1873 to 1874. Since Josephine had died in 1868, Margaret was an acting First Lady for social and official functions.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|27}}\n\n==Community activity==\nWhile in Denver, she led committee meetings in her home. She was a member and officer of educational, religious, and charitable organizations.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|23}} In addition to the projects that she enacted, she was a co-partner in her husband's educational and civic efforts. According to author Helen Canon, \"She brought to these new tasks purposeful ambition, a vigorous mind, a Puritan conscience which forbade her to waste time, and a personal philosophy that 'a New Englander must never be beaten.'\"<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|27}} \n\nIn 1872, she established the Denver Orphan's Home due to encouragement by Byers and contributions by other women.<ref name=\"Beaton p. 50\" /> She was president of the Board of Directors the first year.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|28}} It was later called the Denver Children's Home. She asked her son, [[William Gray Evans]], who operated the [[Denver Tramway|Denver Tramway Company]] to let children ride for free.<ref name=\"Beaton p. 50\">{{Cite book |last=Beaton |first=Gail M. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uwceDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA50 |title=Colorado Women: A History |date=2012-11-15 |publisher=University Press of Colorado |isbn=978-1-60732-207-8 |pages=50 |language=en}}</ref> In 1872<ref name=\"Catlett\" /> or 1875, she co-founded the [[Frances Wisebart Jacobs#Denver Ladies' Relief Society|Ladies Relief Society]] with Elizabeth Byers and [[Frances Wisebart Jacobs]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Beaton |first=Gail M. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uwceDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA112 |title=Colorado Women: A History |date=2012-11-15 |publisher=University Press of Colorado |isbn=978-1-60732-207-8 |page=112 |language=en}}</ref> It was reorganized from the Ladies Aid Society that Byers founded in 1860.<ref name=\"Catlett\">{{Cite book |last=Catlett |first=Sharon R. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tq-lga6iFbEC&pg=PA14 |title=Farmlands, Forts, and Country Life: The Story of Southwest Denver |date=2007 |publisher=Big Earth Publishing |isbn=978-1-56579-545-7 |page=14 |language=en}}</ref> Byers and Evans founded the Old Ladies Home in 1873.<ref name=\"Catlett\" />\n\n[[File:Evans Memorial Chapel.JPG|thumb|left|[[Evans Memorial Chapel]] codesigned by John and Margaret Gray Evans and built by John Evans after the death of his daughter, [[Josephine Evans Elbert]]. It is located on the [[University of Denver]] campus]]\nShe and her husband were involved in the design and construction of two Gothic churches, [[Evans Memorial Chapel]], built in the memory of [[Josephine Evans Elbert]] and dedicated on\nOctober 10, 1878, and the Grace Methodist Church, which was dedicated on January 27, 1889.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|28}} She served on the Colorado Seminary (now [[University of Denver]]) board of trustees from 1880 to 1900 and was a patron of the school's Fine Arts department. She was the president of the Board of Control when the department was reorganized as the Denver School of Fine Arts in 1892. In 1884, she chaired a committee to establish a woman's chair in the University of Denver. The committee of 20 women raised $30,000. From 1888 to 1891, [[Mary Lowe Dickinson]] was the Woman's Chair of ''[[Belles-lettres]]''. She was a friend of Evans.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|28}} \n\nShe was a member of the Women's Club of Denver and was listed among the members who were \"reformers, suffragists, and public servants\", along with [[Alice Hale Hill]], [[Elizabeth Iliff Warren]], [[Eliza Pickrell Routt|Elizabeth F. Routt]], [[Elizabeth Byers]], [[Ella Denison]], and [[Margaret P. Campbell]].<ref name=\"Beaton\" /> She was a member and president of the Denver Fortnight Club which was a \"union of congenial minds for study and discussion and for the furtherance of good in practical ways.\" It was established in 1881. In 1889, it was renamed the Monday Literary Club.<ref name=\"Beaton\">{{Cite book |last=Beaton |first=Gail M. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uwceDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA100 |title=Colorado Women: A History |date=2012-11-15 |publisher=University Press of Colorado |isbn=978-1-60732-207-8 |pages=100, 101 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nShe joined the Denver Artists' Club in 1893, as did her daughter Anne. It became the [[Denver Art Museum]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.historycolorado.org/anne-evans |title=Anne Evans  |website=History Colorado |access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Europe==\nShe lived in Europe during two periods where she sought to improve her health, study and travel. She went to Europe in the fall of 1870 and established a home in London where her daughter [[Anne Evans (arts patron)|Anne Evans]] was born on January 23, 1871. She returned to Colorado that winter. She returned to London in May 1875 and traveled on the Continent. She returned to Colorado in April 1877.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|27}}\n\n==Death==\nJohn Evans died in 1897 after which he lie in state in the capitol rotunda. He was buried in [[Riverside Cemetery (Denver, Colorado)|Riverside Cemetery]] in Denver.<ref name=\"DPL\" /> His estate passed to Margaret.<ref name=\"Northwestern Study\" />\n\n[[File:Byers-Evans House, Denver, about 1889.png|thumb|[[Byers\u2013Evans House]], Denver, about 1889, when the photograph was taken of Evans family members. It was the home of William Gray Evans beginning 1889. In 1900, [[Margaret Gray Evans]] and her daughter [[Anne Evans (arts patron)|Anne Evans]] moved into the house.]]\nMargaret Evans died on September 7, 1906 in Denver, Colorado and is buried next to her husband at Riverside Cemetery.<ref name=\"DPL\" /> Her diaries and papers are held in the collections of the Denver Public Library.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://eadsrv.denverlibrary.org/sdx/pl/doc-tdm.xsp?id=WH1724_d0e444&fmt=text&base=fa&root=&n=&qid=&ss=&as=&ai= |title=Margaret Gray Evans papers |website=The Denver Public Library |access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{findagrave|32945067}}\n\n[[Category:1830 births]]\n[[Category:1906 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bowdoinham, Maine]]\n[[Category:People from Denver]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from Colorado]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Margaret Gray Evans.png|thumb|Margaret Gray Evans, wife of [[John Evans (Colorado governor)|John Evans]], governor of [[Colorado Territory]], Northwestern University Archives]]\n'''Margaret Gray Evans''' (August 21, 1830\u2013September 7, 1906) was the wife of Territorial Governor [[John Evans (Colorado governor)|John Evans]] and was a philanthropist. She arrived in Denver when it was a rough city, having grown up in a privileged home in Maine. Evans was First Lady of Colorado for her husband and her son-in-law, [[Samuel Hitt Elbert]], who was a widower when he became governor. She was known for creating Denver society for the manner in which she entertained in what was the executive manor in Colorado. She assisted her husband on his educational and civil projects, and created her own. She founded the Denver Orphan's Home and was involved in the establishment of literary and charitable organizations. She was also active on boards of the [[University of Denver]]. She was the mother of [[William Gray Evans]] and [[Anne Evans (arts patron)|Anne Evans]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nMargaret Patten Gray was born on August 21, 1830<ref name=\"DPL\">{{Cite web |url=http://eadsrv.denverlibrary.org/sdx/pl/doc-tdm.xsp?id=WH1724_d0e34&fmt=text&base=fa |title=Governor John Evans Papers, WH1724, Western History Collection |website=The Denver Public Library  |access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref><ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|19}} in [[Bowdoinham, Maine]]. She was one of nine children born to Susan Felton Gray and Samuel Gray, a lawyer and shipbuilder.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|19}}\n\n[[Image:Mayflower in Plymouth Harbor, by William Halsall.jpg|thumb|''Mayflower in Plymouth Harbor'' by [[William Halsall]] (1882)]]\nShe is one of the [[Daughters of the American Revolution]] through her great-grandfather Pardon Gray and a descendent of two men on the ''[[Mayflower]]'', [[Francis Cooke]] and [[Richard Warren]].<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|19}}\n\nHer sister Cornelia married [[Orrington Lunt]], a wealthy grain broker who also helped found [[Northwestern University]] with John Evans. [[Paul Cornell (lawyer)|Paul Cornell]], an attorney, married another sister. Cornell was a real estate developer who founded\nthe town of [[Hyde Park, Illinois]].<ref name=\"Northwestern Study\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.northwestern.edu/provost/committees/equity-and-inclusion/study-committee-report.pdf|title=Report of the John Evans Study Committee: Chapter Two - The Life and Career of John Evans |date=May 2014 |website=Northwestern University |access-date=February 7, 2020|pages=15\u201317, 99}}</ref>\n\n==Marriage and children==\nMargaret Gray married John Evans August 18, 1853 in Bowdoinham, Maine.<ref name=\"DPL\" /><ref name=\"Northwestern Study\" /> It was the second marriage for John Evans, whose wife, Hannah Canby Evans, died of [[tuberculosis]] in 1850. She had a step-daughter, [[Josephine Evans Elbert|Josephine Evans]], the only surviving child from his first marriage.<ref name=\"Northwestern Study\" /> The family moved to Chicago in 1855.<ref name=\"Northwestern Study\" /> \n\nMargaret and John's children are:\n* [[William Gray Evans]], born on December 16, 1855 in Chicago<ref name=\"DPL\" /><ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|20}}\n* Margaret Evans, born October 3, 1857 in Chicago and died at age 5 of [[scarlet fever]] in 1862<ref name=\"DPL\" /><ref name=\"Northwestern Study\" /><ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|20\u201321}} \n* Evan Elbert Evans, born June 26, 1863 in Evanston, Illinois<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|23}}{{efn|Evan is said to be born in Denver,<ref name=\"DPL\" /> but an article about Margaret Gray Evans states that she returned to Evanston for the birth of their child.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|23}}}} Married to Kathryn Farrell of West Virginia, his stepdaughter was Madelyn Evans. He was a businessman in California, and then ran the Evans Investment Company. He died in 1921.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://research.frick.org/directory/viewItem/4777 |title=Archives Directory for the History of Collecting in America |website=research.frick.org |access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Anne Evans (arts patron)|Anne Evans]] born January 23, 1871<ref name=\"DPL\" /><ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|27}}\n\nTheir daughter, Margaret, died a few months after John Evans moved to Denver while the rest of the family remained in [[Evanston, Illinois]].<ref name=\"Northwestern Study\" /> Margaret and her son William moved to Colorado in November 1862 when her husband had sufficiently settled his affairs. They initially lived at Tremont House while their house was built. Josephine went away to school at the [[Wilbraham Wesleyan Academy]] in Wilbraham, Massachusetts. After she completed her schooling, she moved to Denver in late January 1864.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|21\u201322}} \n\nMargaret traveled to Washington, D.C. with her stepdaughter Josephine and niece Cornelia Gray Lunt to attend [[Abraham Lincoln]]'s second inauguration. She also traveled to Evanston when Josephine married [[Samuel Hitt Elbert]] in 1865 at the Evanston home.<ref name=\"Northwestern Study\" /><ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|23}} Josephine had a child who died in 1868. She died of tuberculosis in 1868.<ref name=\"Northwestern Study\" />\n\nMargaret lived in London, England in the mid-1870s, during which John Evans had experienced losses due to mining and railroad investments.<ref name=\"Northwestern Study\" />\n\n==First Lady==\n[[File:John Evans House, Denver, about 1870s.png|thumb|John Evans House, Denver, about 1870s]]\nShe became the First Lady of the Colorado Territory when her husband became the Territorial governor of [[Colorado Territory]] in 1862. Since [[William Gilpin (governor)|William Gilpin]], the first governor, was a bachelor, she was the first First Lady. Their home at 14th and Arapahoe Streets in Denver was the executive manor of the territory. While houses at the time were rough, low-roofed cabins, they lived in a one and a half story brick house. She built a significant library in the house. They lived there from 1863 to 1900.<ref name=\"First Ladies\">{{Cite magazine |last=Cannon |first=Helen |date=January 1962 |title=First Ladies of Colorado-Margaret Gray Evans  |url=https://www.historycolorado.org/sites/default/files/media/document/2018/ColoradoMagazine_v39n1_January1962.pdf |magazine=Colorado Magazine |pages=19-28 |access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|19, 21\u2013 23}}\n\nDuring her husband's administration, there was a flood and fire in Denver, famine, and fear of attacks by Native Americans.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|23}} Despite the difficulties, she organized Denver society with her friends who were also well-educated and dignified. People of the period stated that Denver society began with Margaret Gray Evans when she and her husband began entertaining members of the legislature in their home. It was the beginning of the many times that Margaret and her husband entertained. She was known for creating elegant evenings of music, lively conversation, and joy. Her skills were learned from \"the hospitable\nand cultured but precise New England home of her girlhood.\"<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|23\u201325}}\n\nIn the 1870s, she supervised the expansion of their home into a three-story house, which served again as an executive manor when her son-in-law became the governor from 1873 to 1874. Since Josephine had died in 1868, Margaret was an acting First Lady for social and official functions.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|27}}\n\n==Community activity==\nWhile in Denver, she led committee meetings in her home. She was a member and officer of educational, religious, and charitable organizations.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|23}} In addition to the projects that she enacted, she was a co-partner in her husband's educational and civic efforts. According to author Helen Canon, \"She brought to these new tasks purposeful ambition, a vigorous mind, a Puritan conscience which forbade her to waste time, and a personal philosophy that 'a New Englander must never be beaten.'\"<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|27}} \n\nIn 1872, she established the Denver Orphan's Home due to encouragement by Byers and contributions by other women.<ref name=\"Beaton p. 50\" /> She was president of the Board of Directors the first year.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|28}} It was later called the Denver Children's Home. She asked her son, [[William Gray Evans]], who operated the [[Denver Tramway|Denver Tramway Company]] to let children ride for free.<ref name=\"Beaton p. 50\">{{Cite book |last=Beaton |first=Gail M. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uwceDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA50 |title=Colorado Women: A History |date=2012-11-15 |publisher=University Press of Colorado |isbn=978-1-60732-207-8 |pages=50 |language=en}}</ref> In 1872<ref name=\"Catlett\" /> or 1875, she co-founded the [[Frances Wisebart Jacobs#Denver Ladies' Relief Society|Ladies Relief Society]] with Elizabeth Byers and [[Frances Wisebart Jacobs]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Beaton |first=Gail M. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uwceDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA112 |title=Colorado Women: A History |date=2012-11-15 |publisher=University Press of Colorado |isbn=978-1-60732-207-8 |page=112 |language=en}}</ref> It was reorganized from the Ladies Aid Society that Byers founded in 1860.<ref name=\"Catlett\">{{Cite book |last=Catlett |first=Sharon R. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tq-lga6iFbEC&pg=PA14 |title=Farmlands, Forts, and Country Life: The Story of Southwest Denver |date=2007 |publisher=Big Earth Publishing |isbn=978-1-56579-545-7 |page=14 |language=en}}</ref> Byers and Evans founded the Old Ladies Home in 1873.<ref name=\"Catlett\" />\n\n[[File:Evans Memorial Chapel.JPG|thumb|left|[[Evans Memorial Chapel]] codesigned by John and Margaret Gray Evans and built by John Evans after the death of his daughter, [[Josephine Evans Elbert]]. It is located on the [[University of Denver]] campus]]\nShe and her husband were involved in the design and construction of two Gothic churches, [[Evans Memorial Chapel]], built in the memory of [[Josephine Evans Elbert]] and dedicated on\nOctober 10, 1878, and the Grace Methodist Church, which was dedicated on January 27, 1889.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|28}} She served on the Colorado Seminary (now [[University of Denver]]) board of trustees from 1880 to 1900 and was a patron of the school's Fine Arts department. She was the president of the Board of Control when the department was reorganized as the Denver School of Fine Arts in 1892. In 1884, she chaired a committee to establish a woman's chair in the University of Denver. The committee of 20 women raised $30,000. From 1888 to 1891, [[Mary Lowe Dickinson]] was the Woman's Chair of ''[[Belles-lettres]]''. She was a friend of Evans.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|28}} \n\nShe was a member of the Women's Club of Denver and was listed among the members who were \"reformers, suffragists, and public servants\", along with [[Alice Hale Hill]], [[Elizabeth Iliff Warren]], [[Eliza Pickrell Routt|Elizabeth F. Routt]], [[Elizabeth Byers]], [[Ella Denison]], and [[Margaret P. Campbell]].<ref name=\"Beaton\" /> She was a member and president of the Denver Fortnight Club which was a \"union of congenial minds for study and discussion and for the furtherance of good in practical ways.\" It was established in 1881. In 1889, it was renamed the Monday Literary Club.<ref name=\"Beaton\">{{Cite book |last=Beaton |first=Gail M. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uwceDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA100 |title=Colorado Women: A History |date=2012-11-15 |publisher=University Press of Colorado |isbn=978-1-60732-207-8 |pages=100, 101 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nShe joined the Denver Artists' Club in 1893, as did her daughter Anne. It became the [[Denver Art Museum]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.historycolorado.org/anne-evans |title=Anne Evans  |website=History Colorado |access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Europe==\nShe lived in Europe during two periods where she sought to improve her health, study and travel. She went to Europe in the fall of 1870 and established a home in London where her daughter [[Anne Evans (arts patron)|Anne Evans]] was born on January 23, 1871. She returned to Colorado that winter. She returned to London in May 1875 and traveled on the Continent. She returned to Colorado in April 1877.<ref name=\"First Ladies\" />{{rp|27}}\n\n==Death==\nJohn Evans died in 1897 after which he lie in state in the capitol rotunda. He was buried in [[Riverside Cemetery (Denver, Colorado)|Riverside Cemetery]] in Denver.<ref name=\"DPL\" /> His estate passed to Margaret.<ref name=\"Northwestern Study\" />\n\n[[File:Byers-Evans House, Denver, about 1889.png|thumb|[[Byers\u2013Evans House]], Denver, about 1889, when the photograph was taken of Evans family members. It was the home of William Gray Evans beginning 1889. In 1900, [[Margaret Gray Evans]] and her daughter [[Anne Evans (arts patron)|Anne Evans]] moved into the house.]]\nMargaret Evans died on September 7, 1906 in Denver, Colorado and is buried next to her husband at Riverside Cemetery.<ref name=\"DPL\" /> Her diaries and papers are held in the collections of the Denver Public Library.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://eadsrv.denverlibrary.org/sdx/pl/doc-tdm.xsp?id=WH1724_d0e444&fmt=text&base=fa&root=&n=&qid=&ss=&as=&ai= |title=Margaret Gray Evans papers |website=The Denver Public Library |access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{findagrave|32945067}}\n\n[[Category:1830 births]]\n[[Category:1906 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bowdoinham, Maine]]\n[[Category:People from Denver]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from Colorado]]\n", "name_user": "PohranicniStraze", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margaret_Gray_Evans"}
